Aggregated cheatsheets of all tutorials

Martin Raden

This aggregated cheatsheet of our tutorial package Introduction to programming with R summarizes the individual notes from the provided tutorials and additional information from recommended sources.

R, RStudio, coding, packages

  • == operator tests for equality of things; != for inequality
  • = is used for assignment of values to arguments (dont use for object assignment!)
  • Boolean statements work on and result in TRUE/FALSE values
    • can be combined using logical operators like & (AND), | (OR), and ! (NOT)
  • functions, aka commands, are the workhorses in R and always come with a () after their name
  • c() combines/concatenates multiple values into one vector object
  • install.packages() installs a new package via its name from the console (also possible via Packages menu in RStudio)
  • a package is a collection of additional functions and data objects, examples are
    • ggplot2 for visualization
    • dplyr for data transformation
    • important packages for data processing covered in this course are loaded via the meta-package tidyverse
  • library() loads a package via its name
    • this command is typically missing if your R doesnt know/find the function you want to use!

Cheatsheet first-steps

  • in tidy tabular data
    • a row represents one observation, i.e.a single thing you want to talk about
    • a column is a variable, i.e.a feature that might be vary between observations

Cheatsheet ggplot-basics

  • help() provides details information on functions, data sets, packages
    • ? short version
  • head() first elements of object
  • glimpse() (from dplyr package) compact variable view of tabular data
    • one line per variable column
    • Summary page
  • ggplot2 is the visualization package
    • ggplot() defines what data to plot (and general/shared aesthetics)
    • aes() aesthetics define what data variables are used where in the plot, i.e.their mapping
    • geom_...() defines how to plot the data, i.e.the plot geometry, e.g.
      • geom_point() (Summary page)
      • geom_line() (Summary page)
      • geom_smooth() (Summary page)
    • + combines different geometries etc. into one plot
  • R combines multiple lines into one call if at the end of a line
    • there is an operator like +, <-, =,
    • it misses still a closing bracket or brace, i.e.), ], }, or closing quote, i.e.", '

Workflow basics

  • variable names
    • can contain numbers, letters, . and _
    • have to start with a letter
    • should be self-explanatory
    • capitalization matters, i.e.myname is not myName
  • use <- for object assignment (RStudio hot key = ALT + -)
  • seq() generates a vector of subsequent numbers, e.g.seq(2,5) is equal to c(2,3,4,5)
  • text/string/character values have to be quoted, i.e.surrounded by ticks
    • use either '' or "", both works
    • ensure closing tick for any opening
  • writing a variable name in the console prints it, i.e.x is equal to print(x)
    • surrounding a term in round brackets () triggers printing implicitly
  • RStudio: hot key ALT+SHIFT+K shows all hot key combinations

Cheatsheet dplyr-filter

  • vector creation via c() (concatenate)
  • conditional statements/functions result in logical values (TRUE or FALSE)
    • ==, !=, >, <, <=, >=
    • &, |, xor()
    • !
    • %in% vector (or counterpart %notin%)
    • between() (dplyr)
    • near() better for floating point number comparison than ==
  • filter() prunes table to rows of interest (Summary page)
    • all rows for which the conditional statement is TRUE pass the filter and are kept; all others are removed
    • multiple sequential filter steps separated by comma or &
    • direct use of variable (column) names in filter criteria
    • brackets in conditional statements are often important!
  • %>% piping for connection of data transformation steps
    • (first) input argument of subsequent function automatically set (with result of last)
  • summary() statistical overview of values in data structure; e.g.for each variable of a data frame

Cheatsheet dplyr-arrange-select

  • arrange() changes the order of rows (Summary page)
    • multiple (comma-separated) variable names define a sorting hierarchy (left-to-right) that is used for tie breaking
    • default = ascending order
    • desc() around a variable triggers descending sorting w.r.t. the variables values
    • NA is always last
  • select() reduces the columns to variables of interest (Summary page)
    • comma-separated variable list or vector notation (using c())
      • : generates a vector of ascendingly increasing elements (from:to) including the boundaries
      • specified order = new order of columns (can be used for reordering)
        • everything() : all variables not named so far (useful for reordering of columns)
        • duplicated names are ignored
    • ! or - negation removes the specified variables (also works for vectors via c() or :)
    • selection can be specified via names (quoted and unquoted) as well as numbers
    • starts_with(), ends_with(), contains() : parts of variable names
    • matches() : regular expression on names (discussed later)
    • num_range() : combines strings and number vectors to full names like x1, x2,
    • any_of() : listed variable names not necessarily present in data table (useful for negative selection without errors/warnings)

Cheatsheet dplyr-mutate

  • mutate() creates new variables (columns) (Summary page)
    • format is NAME = EXPRESSION
    • multiple variables can be created (subsequently) in one mutate() calls
      • you can directly use previously created variables
  • transmute() creates a new table with new variables (dropping the input table)
    • produces one row for each row of the input table
  • creation functions
    • are done row-wise on the whole column at once
      • i.e.when computing A-B, respective A and B values from each row from both columns are subtracted (creating a new vector with the same length as both columns; one result for each row in the same row-order)
    • if a function works that way it is called a vectorized functions
    • common operations:
      • arithmetic operations (for numbers only): +, -, *, /, ^ (power), log..()
      • modular operations (for integers only): %/% and %%
      • logical comparison: <, ==, !=, >=,
      • logical operations (working on TRUE/FALSE): &, |, !
      • cum...() = rolling , e.g.
        • cumsum()/cumprod = rolling sum/product of consecutive values (= vector of values)
        • cummin()/cummax = min/max of all rows up to here
        • cummean()
      • rank of each value (within sorted order of values within variable), e.g.
        • min_rank() or dense_rank() (typically one of both is what you are looking for)
        • or percent_rank(), row_number(),
      • offset, i.e.column is shifted up or down by n rows
        • lag() = previous values, i.e.shifting the column down (NAs at the beginning)
        • lead() = following values, i.e.shiting the column up (NAs at the end)
      • aggregative functions like
        • sum() = sum of all values in the variable column (= single value)
        • mean()
  • recycling rule = if one operator element is too small, it is repeated to the needed length!
    • longer length needs to be multiple of shorter length!
    • e.g.both c(1,2,3,4)+1 and c(1,2,3,4)+c(1,2) are working while c(1,2,3)+c(1,2) is not
    • best use with single values only!

Cheatsheet dplyr-groupby-summarize

  • summarize() produces only a single output row (per group) (Summary page)
    • computes statistical properties of variables (or combinations)
    • when statistics on groups: good idea to report/check group size via n()
    • consumes a previous grouping via group_by(), i.e.merges the rows per group into one table
  • group_by() decomposes the observations (Summary page)
    • i.e.decomposing the table into subtables that show the same value w.r.t. the grouping variable
    • multiple grouping variables can be given (comma-separated) to specific a grouping hierarchy
    • subsequent group_by() calls overwrite the grouping of the previous!
    • all subsequent operations or done independently per group
  • ungroup() explicitly undoes the previous group_by() and merges the subtables back into one
  • aggregation functions
    • mean(), median(), quantile(), Sd()
    • min(), max(), first(), last(), nth()
    • n(), n_distinct()
    • sum()
      • sum() of logical values == number of TRUEs (since scored 1, where FALSE is scored 0)
    • can be used anywhere, also in mutate(), filter(),
    • NA handling important (set na.rm=TRUE argument if wanted)
  • count() is a summary based on counting or summation only

Cheatsheet dplyr-sundries

  • rename() allows to alter variable names (Summary page)
    • format: <NEWNAME> = <OLDVAR> where OLDVAR can be
      • an index number or
      • the old name of the column to rename
  • colnames() give you the vector of a tables column names (base R)
  • slice functions extract specific rows (Summary page)
    • slice() - columns specified by indices
    • slice_min(), slice_max() - best/worst rows w.r.t. values in a given variable
    • slice_head(), slice_tail() - top/tail rows w.r.t. current row order
    • slice_sample() - pick at random
    • set n=.. argument for number of rows
    • set prop=.. argument to specify a fraction of rows to keep
    • be aware of ranking ties during min/max slicing
  • distinct() reduces the table to unique observations (Summary page)
    • if a (set of) variable name(s) is given, only first rows with a unique value combination w.r.t. the named variables are kept
    • .keep_all=TRUE no columns are removed from the output
  • join functions allow to fuse information from multiple tables into one
    • this is called a mutating join (Summary page)
    • increases data redundancy but allows for subsequent tidy data analyses and ggplot visualizations
    • joining is done based on equal values in respective key columns
      • by = X - same column name X in both tables
      • by = c(X = Y) - merge based on X column in first table and Y variable from second table
    • missing values produce NA entries
    • left_join() keeps all rows from first table
    • inner_join() - only observations with values in both tables
    • full_join() - all vs.all combinations
  • dplyr package cover even more verbs, see
    • dplyr reference page
    • Cheatsheet
